h1(Server API: Complete Reference)
h3(Everything you need to know about building OBLIT servers.)

The <code>Server</code> class is the heart of any OBLIT application. It provides an event-driven, high-performance TCP server with automatic stream reassembly and crash-free error handling.

![info](All Server instances extend Node.js's EventEmitter, so you can use familiar event patterns. The API is intentionally minimal but powerful.)!++

!(line)

h2(ğŸ“¦ Constructor)

h3(<code>new Server(options)</code>)

Creates a new server instance. The server does **not** start listening until you call <code>st()</code>.

<div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Type</th><th>Default</th><th>Required</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>options</code></td><td><code>Object</code></td><td><code>{}</code></td><td>No</td><td>Configuration object for the server</td></tr><tr><td><code>options.port</code></td><td><code>Number</code></td><td><code>3000</code></td><td>No</td><td>The TCP port number to bind to (0-65535)</td></tr><tr><td><code>options.silent</code></td><td><code>Boolean</code></td><td><code>false</code></td><td>No</code></td><td>If <code>true</code>, suppresses all internal error logging</td></tr></tbody></table></div>

<h3(Usage Examples)

<div style="display:grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(300px, 1fr)); gap:20px; margin:25px 0;">

<div style="background:var(--box-info-bg); padding:20px; border-radius:8px; border-left:4px solid var(--primary);">
<strong style="color:var(--primary);">ğŸ“Œ Default Port (3000)</strong><br><br>
<code style="background:transparent;">const server = new Server();<br>// Listens on port 3000</code>
</div>

<div style="background:var(--box-tip-bg); padding:20px; border-radius:8px; border-left:4px solid #22c55e;">
<strong style="color:#22c55e;">ğŸ“Œ Custom Port</strong><br><br>
<code style="background:transparent;">const server = new Server({ port: 8080 });<br>// Listens on port 8080</code>
</div>

<div style="background:var(--box-warn-bg); padding:20px; border-radius:8px; border-left:4px solid #f97316;">
<strong style="color:#f97316;">ğŸ“Œ Silent Mode</strong><br><br>
<code style="background:transparent;">const server = new Server({<br>  port: 9000,<br>  silent: true<br>});<br>// No error logs</code>
</div>

</div>

!(line)

h2(âš™ï¸ Methods)

h3(<code>server.st([callback])</code>)

Starts the TCP listener and begins accepting connections. This is an alias for <code>start()</code>â€”shorter for convenience.

<div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Type</th><th>Required</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>callback</code></td><td><code>Function</code></td><td>No</td><td>Called once when the server successfully starts listening. Receives no arguments.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>

<h3(Examples)

![code](const { Server } = require('oblit');

const app = new Server({ port: 8080 });

// Start with callback
app.st(() => {
    console.log('âœ… Server started on port 8080');
    console.log('Ready to accept connections!');
});

// Or start without callback
app.st();)!++//

![tip](The callback is useful for initialization tasks like loading game state, connecting to databases, or sending "server ready" notifications.)!++

h3(<code>server.bc(message)</code>)

Broadcasts a message to **all** currently connected clients. This is an alias for <code>broadcast()</code>.

<div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Type</th><th>Required</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>message</code></td><td><code>String | Object | Buffer</code></td><td>Yes</td><td>The data to broadcast. Type is automatically detected (TXT/JSON/RAW).</td></tr></tbody></table></div>

<h3(Performance Details)

<div style="background:var(--box-tip-bg); padding:20px; border-radius:8px; margin:20px 0; border-left:4px solid #22c55e;">
<strong style="color:#22c55e;">âš¡ Optimization:</strong><br><br>
OBLIT packs the data **once** and writes the same buffer reference to all connected sockets. This means:
<ul style="margin:10px 0 0 0;">
<li>âœ… Zero memory overhead per client</li>
<li>âœ… Minimal CPU usage</li>
<li>âœ… Fastest possible broadcast</li>
</ul>
</div>

<h3(Examples)

![code](const app = new Server({ port: 8080 });

app.on('data', (message, socket) => {
    // Broadcast text message
    app.bc(`User said: ${message}`);

    // Broadcast JSON object
    app.bc({ type: 'chat', user: socket.remoteAddress, text: message });

    // Broadcast binary data
    const gameState = Buffer.from([1, 2, 3, 4]);
    app.bc(gameState);
});

app.st();)!++//

![info](Broadcast is one-way only. Clients won't receive responses to their own broadcasts. If you need bidirectional communication, use the <code>socket</code> parameter in the <code>'data'</code> event.)!++

!(line)

h2(ğŸ“¡ Events)

The Server class extends EventEmitter, so you can use all standard EventEmitter methods (<code>on</code>, <code>once</code>, <code>off</code>, etc.).

h3(<code>'data'</code> Event)

Emitted whenever a complete packet is received from a client. This is the primary event for handling incoming messages.

<div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Event Name</th><th>Callback Arguments</th><th>When Emitted</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>'data'</code></td><td><code>(message, socket)</code></td><td>When a complete packet arrives from any client</td></tr></tbody></table></div>

<h3(Callback Parameters)

<div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>message</code></td><td><code>String | Object | Buffer</code></td><td>The unpacked payload. Type depends on the OpCode sent by client.</td></tr><tr><td><code>socket</code></td><td><code>net.Socket</code></td><td>The Node.js socket object of the client that sent the message. Use this to send replies or identify clients.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>

<h3(Examples)

![code](const { Server, OP } = require('oblit');
const core = require('oblit/src/c');

const app = new Server({ port: 8080 });

// Handle text messages
app.on('data', (message, socket) => {
    console.log(`Received from ${socket.remoteAddress}:`, message);

    // Send reply to the sender only
    if (message === 'PING') {
        const pongPacket = core.p(OP.TXT, 'PONG');
        socket.write(pongPacket);
    }

    // Broadcast to everyone else
    if (typeof message === 'string' && message.startsWith('!')) {
        app.bc(`Announcement: ${message.substring(1)}`);
    }
});

// Handle JSON objects
app.on('data', (message, socket) => {
    if (typeof message === 'object' && !Buffer.isBuffer(message)) {
        if (message.type === 'login') {
            console.log(`User ${message.username} logged in`);
            socket.playerId = message.username;
        }
    }
});

// Handle binary data
app.on('data', (message, socket) => {
    if (Buffer.isBuffer(message)) {
        // Process game coordinates, sensor data, etc.
        const playerId = message.readUInt16BE(0);
        const x = message.readUInt16BE(2);
        const y = message.readUInt16BE(4);
        console.log(`Player ${playerId} moved to (${x}, ${y})`);
    }
});

app.st();)!++//

h3(<code>'connect'</code> Event)

Emitted when a new client successfully connects to the server.

<div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Event Name</th><th>Callback Arguments</th><th>When Emitted</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>'connect'</code></td><td><code>(socket)</code></td><td>Immediately after a new client establishes a TCP connection</td></tr></tbody></table></div>

<h3(Examples)

![code](const app = new Server({ port: 8080 });

app.on('connect', (socket) => {
    const clientId = `${socket.remoteAddress}:${socket.remotePort}`;
    console.log(`âœ… New connection: ${clientId}`);

    // Store custom data on socket
    socket.connectedAt = Date.now();
    socket.playerId = null;

    // Send welcome message
    const welcome = { type: 'welcome', message: 'Connected to server!' };
    app.bc(welcome);
});

app.st();)!++//

h3(<code>'disconnect'</code> Event)

Emitted when a client disconnects (gracefully or unexpectedly).

<div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Event Name</th><th>Callback Arguments</th><th>When Emitted</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>'disconnect'</code></td><td><code>(socket)</code></td><td>When a client's TCP connection is closed</td></tr></tbody></table></div>

<h3(Examples)

![code](const app = new Server({ port: 8080 });

app.on('disconnect', (socket) => {
    const clientId = socket.playerId || `${socket.remoteAddress}:${socket.remotePort}`;
    console.log(`âŒ Client disconnected: ${clientId}`);

    // Cleanup
    if (socket.playerId) {
        delete gameState.players[socket.playerId];
    }

    // Notify other clients
    app.bc({ type: 'player_left', playerId: socket.playerId });
});

app.st();)!++//

h3(<code>'error'</code> Event)

Emitted when a server-level error occurs (e.g., port already in use).

<div class="table-wrapper"><table><thead><tr><th>Event Name</th><th>Callback Arguments</th><th>When Emitted</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><code>'error'</code></td><td><code>(error)</code></td><td>When a server-level error occurs</td></tr></tbody></table></div>

<h3(Examples)

![code](const app = new Server({ port: 8080 });

app.on('error', (error) => {
    console.error('âŒ Server error:', error.message);

    if (error.code === 'EADDRINUSE') {
        console.log('Port 8080 is already in use. Trying port 8081...');
        app.st(); // This won't work, but shows the pattern
    }
});

app.st();)!++//

!(line)

h2(ğŸ’¡ Best Practices)

<div style="display:grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr)); gap:15px; margin:25px 0;">

<div style="background:var(--box-tip-bg); padding:20px; border-radius:8px; border-left:4px solid #22c55e;">
<strong style="color:#22c55e;">âœ… Store Client Data</strong><br><br>
Attach custom properties to the <code>socket</code> object to track client state:
<code style="background:transparent;">socket.playerId = 'user123';</code>
</div>

<div style="background:var(--box-warn-bg); padding:20px; border-radius:8px; border-left:4px solid #f97316;">
<strong style="color:#f97316;">âš ï¸ Handle Errors</strong><br><br>
Always listen for the <code>'error'</code> event to handle server-level issues gracefully.
</div>

<div style="background:var(--box-info-bg); padding:20px; border-radius:8px; border-left:4px solid var(--primary);">
<strong style="color:var(--primary);">ğŸ“¦ Use Binary for Games</strong><br><br>
For high-frequency data (like player positions), use Buffer/RAW mode for maximum performance.
</div>

</div>

![tip](Want to see a complete working example? Check out the **[Chat Tutorial](#!/tut_chat)** or **[Game Server Tutorial](#!/tut_game)** for real-world implementations.)!++

